description: The 12th Annual Porcupine Hill Climb is a 14.7 mile climb up Utah\'s Big Cottonwood Canyon to Brighton Ski Resort with nearly 3,800 feet of elevation gain. title: Tour de Park City fun Ride
Larry H. Miller Tour of Utah
The Ultimate Challenge
description: Please visit our website for complete details
course:
Option 1: Newpark Town Center to Midway: 35 miles.

From Park City, riders will head east on SR 248 around the town of Kamas and the Jordanelle Reservoir. With only a small climb by the reservoir, riders will have a chance to stretch their legs and gradually warm up before tackling some of the bigger challenges on the ride. Remaining flat to rolling terrain, riders will continue into the picturesque town of Midway. Riders have the option of finishing in Midway and can spend the day relaxing and watching the Tour of Utah in one of our viewing tents.

Option 2: Newpark Town Center to Alpine: 74 miles.

After leaving Midway, riders continue south on rolling terrain and will make their way to the Alpine Scenic Highway. Turning right off of Highway 189 the true challenge begins with the Sundance Climb. At nearly 3000 feet of elevation and 8.7 miles long, this is a formidable challenge. Be prepared to have your breath taken away from the exertion of the climb, altitude, and amazing scenery. Truly an alpine feel as you ride past the magnificent Sundance Ski Resort and through beautiful, lush aspen groves and alpine meadows. At the top of this magnificent climb, refuel and prepare for one of the most challenging descents in the country back down these winding mountain roads into the Salt Lake Basin. These stretches of road even push the most seasoned veterans to the limit. At the bottom of the climb, riders can finish at the 74-mile marker in Alpine, where another viewing tent will offer another location to rest and watch the pros take on the same course.

Option 3: Newpark Town Center to Snowbird Ski and Summer Resort: 100 miles

Riders who choose to ride the full 100 miles will then head north through the communities of Alpine, Draper, and Sandy over rolling terrain and an intermediate climb up over Suncrest Drive. Hopefully riders will have left a little strength in their legs arriving at the bottom of Little Cottonwood Canyon for the final challenge of the day, the Snowbird climb. At six miles in length and climbing 3000 vertical feet of elevation, this is one tough finish. After 100 miles of challenging terrain and elevation changes, riders will welcome the chance to eat, drink, and wait for their favorite pros to cross the finish line.
